arch:property.oc:show_val: North end W CP East, area of robbed pavers (Tr. 97, 2004, Locus 23).
Mix fill between Loci 2 and 4 leveling courses

This is a mixed fill locus containing boulders, wadi/field stones, cobbles, pebbles, as well as soil. One limestone architectural fragment was also recovered. There are two types of compacted soil in the fill: the first is the reddish Petra silt and sand with a Munsell Color in the range between 7.5 YR 5/3-5/4 (Brown); the second seems to be limestone-based silt and sand with a Munsell Color of 10 YR 5/6 (Yellowish Brown). The appearance in the fill of the limestone soil, combined with the high occurrence of water-eroded wadi stones, suggests that some of the material in this locus originated from the flood deposits in the nearby bed of Wadi Musa. The overall deposition appears random, although there was a partial layer of large boulders laid at approximately 893.500 m. This locus represents the thickest distinct stratum in the SP 105 sounding. A relative abundance of small finds came from this locus, including pottery, stucco, bone, metal, and glass. For special finds, there were five definite and three possible coins.
Phase V: Late Nabataean CE 1st c. redesign and repairs.
2.0 m north south-by-4.30 m east west.
